problems.solution:
awk's multi-dimensional arrays (simulated with compound keys) make matrix operations possible.

```awk
{
    rows = NR
    cols = NF
    for (j = 1; j <= NF; j++)
        m[NR][j] = $j
}
END {
    for (j = 1; j <= cols; j++) {
        for (i = 1; i <= rows; i++) {
            printf "%s", m[i][j]
            if (i < rows) printf " "
        }
        printf "\n"
    }
}
```

**Explanation:**
- `m[NR][j]` uses awk's multi-dimensional array syntax. Under the hood, gawk stores `m[NR,j]` as a single string key `NR SUBSEP j`.
- We record `rows` and `cols` as we go (using `NR` and `NF`).
- In `END`, the outer loop iterates over columns (which become rows in the transpose) and the inner loop over rows (which become columns).
- Careful spacing logic avoids a trailing space on each output line.

