problems.solution:
Sorting in awk requires implementing a sort in `END` or using gawk's built-in `asort`/`asorti`.

```awk
{ name[NR] = $1; score[NR] = $2; n = NR }
END {
    # Bubble sort descending by score, stable by original order
    for (i = 1; i <= n; i++)
        for (j = i+1; j <= n; j++)
            if (score[j] > score[i] || (score[j] == score[i] && j < i)) {
                ts = score[i]; score[i] = score[j]; score[j] = ts
                tn = name[i];  name[i]  = name[j];  name[j]  = tn
            }
    for (i = 1; i <= 3 && i <= n; i++)
        print name[i], score[i]
}
```

**Explanation:**
- We store names and scores in parallel arrays indexed by line number.
- In `END`, we bubble sort both arrays together (keeping name/score pairs aligned) in descending score order.
- When scores are tied, original order (lower `j` wins) preserves stability.
- We then print only the first 3 entries.
- For large datasets, gawk's `asorti` or piping to `sort` would be more efficient.

