problems.solution:
A separator line lets us simulate two-file processing from stdin.

```awk
/^---$/ { section++; next }
section == 0 { name[$1]  = $2 }
section == 1 { score[$1] = $2 }
END {
    PROCINFO["sorted_in"] = "@val_str_asc"
    for (id in name)
        result[name[id]] = score[id]
    PROCINFO["sorted_in"] = "@ind_str_asc"
    for (nm in result)
        print nm, result[nm]
}
```

**Explanation:**
- `/^---$/` matches the separator line exactly; `next` skips to the next line without executing other rules.
- `section++` toggles from 0 to 1 when the separator is seen.
- `section == 0` and `section == 1` are **pattern guards** that direct each line to the right array.
- In `END`, we build a `result` array keyed by name for easy alphabetical sorting.
- `PROCINFO["sorted_in"] = "@ind_str_asc"` sorts by key (name) alphabetically.

