problems.solution:
Pivot tables require storing data in a 2D array and controlling output order explicitly.

```awk
BEGIN {
    FS = ","
    split("Jan Feb Mar Apr May Jun Jul Aug Sep Oct Nov Dec", months, " ")
}
NR == 1 { next }  # Skip header
{
    year = $1; month = $2; sales = $3
    pivot[year][month] = sales
    if (!(year in seen_years)) {
        seen_years[year] = 1
        years[++ycount] = year
    }
}
END {
    # Print header
    printf "Year"
    for (m = 1; m <= 12; m++) printf " %s", months[m]
    printf "\n"
    # Sort years numerically
    for (i = 1; i <= ycount; i++)
        for (j = i+1; j <= ycount; j++)
            if (years[j]+0 < years[i]+0) { t=years[i]; years[i]=years[j]; years[j]=t }
    # Print rows
    for (i = 1; i <= ycount; i++) {
        y = years[i]
        printf "%s", y
        for (m = 1; m <= 12; m++) {
            val = (months[m] in pivot[y]) ? pivot[y][months[m]] : 0
            printf " %s", val
        }
        printf "\n"
    }
}
```

**Explanation:**
- `split("Jan Feb ...", months, " ")` populates a 1-indexed array of month names in calendar order — this controls column order in the output.
- `pivot[year][month] = sales` stores data in a nested associative array.
- `seen_years` prevents duplicate year entries; `years` array preserves insertion order before sorting.
- A small bubble sort on `years` ensures chronological order.
- `(months[m] in pivot[y]) ? pivot[y][months[m]] : 0` safely handles missing cells with a ternary expression.
- The whole program is a demonstration of awk's power as a lightweight data transformation tool.

